[1]
Date: Tue 3 Feb 2009
From: Richard Brown <REXROCCO@aol.com>


Re: ProMED-mail Undiagnosed disease & deaths, bovine - Germany: RFI
20090202.0470
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The pathology described sounds remarkably similar to acute bracken
poisoning. Though how this relates to this syndrome in Germany is
hard to see. The toxin in bracken acts significantly against bone
marrow. The complete absence of neutrophils is pathognomonic and was
seen in the one major outbreak I have seen in adult bovines (Belize
1980s ). This outbreak also demonstrated dramatic haemorrhages and
death not unlike anthrax. (All cases we attended were checked out for
anthrax with negative results.) Secondary infections were also likely
in the cases we saw. The mortality in the severely affected was
practically 100 percent. Bracken was present and little other forage
available to eat. It is hard to see how calves so young could have
been exposed to such a toxin or similar so soon after birth unless
some bizarre from of forage management is being practiced. All the
same I would still check out the forage management.

--
Richard Brown MRCVS
Huntly Aberdeenshire
UK
<REXROCCO@aol.com>

