Date: Fri 6 Feb 2009
From: Karen Skelton <Karen.Skelton@dpi.qld.gov.au>


Re: ProMED-mail Undiagnosed disease & deaths, bovine - Germany: RFI
20090202.0470
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The listing on the so-called "blood sweating" syndrome in calves in
Germany was read with interest. Veterinary pathologists at the
Queensland Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries' Animal
Disease Surveillance Laboratory at Toowoomba have seen this type of
syndrome in weaner cattle [calves weaned during the current year.
-Mod.AS] with ptaquiloside poisoning (rock/mulga fern). Fever is due
to secondary bacteraemias associated with severe pancytopaenia. It
was also noted that a similar syndrome was seen years ago with calves
[which] were given unprescribed furazolidone. I understand as with
other countries, the EU banned nitrofurans in the mid 1990's. These
cases were seen in the late 1980's in Queensland and were documented
in the Australian Veterinary Journal, vol 68, 1991, pages 182-3.

[Jim Taylor
Veterinary Pathologist
Animal Disease Surveillance Laboratory
Queensland Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries
203 Tor Street
PO Box 102 Toowoomba
Toowoomba QLD 4350
Australia

--
Karen Skelton
Principal Veterinary Officer (Animal Health Surveillance)
Biosecurity Queensland
Department of Primary Industries & Fisheries
GPO Box 46 Brisbane QLD 4001
<Karen.Skelton@dpi.qld.gov.au>

[Both responders, who are kindly acknowledged, indicate fern
poisoning as the possible cause for the clinical and pathological
changes described from Germany.

For a review addressing the etiology, clinical findings, diagnosis,
treatment, and prevention of bracken fern poisoning, see Merck
Veterinary Manual at
<http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/210400.htm&word=fern%2cpoisoning>.

The Australian commentary mentions also furazolidone as a possible
causative factor. - Mod.AS]

[Bracken (_Pteridium_ spp.) fern does contain ptaquiloside, which
produces a radiomimetic effect on the animals, and thus they would be
more susceptible to bacterial infections. Both contributors are
correct. - Mod.TG]
See Also
Undiagnosed disease & deaths, bovine - Germany: RFI 20090202.0470
